UID:al-purdy-aframe-residency-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T115003Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260918
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260919
SUMMARY:Deadline: Al Purdy A-frame Association: Al and Eurithe Purdy Reside
 ncy 2027
DESCRIPTION:The Al Purdy A-frame Residency offers Canadian writers time and
  space to work at the historic A-frame home built by poet Al Purdy and his
  wife Eurithe on Roblin Lake in Ameliasburgh\, Prince Edward County\, Onta
 rio. Poetry is prioritized\, but all writers are welcome. SUPPORT: CAD 750
  per week stipend and paid return travel (subject to the Association's fun
 draising and Canada Council matching)\; residencies run 3 to 12 weeks. ELI
 GIBILITY: Canadian citizens or permanent residents only. DEADLINE: 18 Sept
 ember 2026 (postmark\, or 4:00pm PT for electronic submissions). Apply via
  the residency page.\n\nOrganisation: The Al Purdy A-frame Association\nLo
 cation: Ameliasburgh\, Prince Edward County\, Ontario\, Canada. Canadian c
 itizens or permanent residents only.\nAward: CAD 750 per week stipend plus
  paid return travel to Ameliasburgh (funding subject to the Association's 
 fundraising and Canada Council matching). Terms of 3 to 12 weeks. No appli
 cation fee.\nDuration: 3 to 12 weeks\n\nMore: https://www.alpurdy.ca/resid
 ency/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.alpurdy.ca/residency/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk
 &utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Ameliasburgh\, Prince Edward County\, Ontario\, Canada. Canadian c
 itizens or permanent residents only.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:insideout-refocus-fund-postproduction-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T115003Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260722
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260723
SUMMARY:Deadline: Inside Out RE:Focus Fund Post-Production Grants 2026
DESCRIPTION:Established in 2018 through a lead gift from Martha McCain\, In
 side Out's RE:Focus Fund addresses industry inequities by providing direct
  financial support to women\, non-binary\, and/or trans filmmakers telling
  2SLGBTQ+ stories. Launched in 2019\, the RE:Focus Fund Post-Production Gr
 ants support the post-production and promotion of short and feature films.
  Applications for the 2026 round open 29 June 2026. ELIGIBILITY: women\, n
 on-binary\, and/or trans filmmakers whose projects tell 2SLGBTQ+ stories\;
  per the FAQ\, international projects may be eligible to apply. The reques
 ted funding amount is determined by the applicant\, and unsuccessful appli
 cants can request feedback and reapply the following year. Inside Out also
  runs other RE:Focus initiatives\, including a new Residency program for f
 irst-time feature filmmakers facing intersectional barriers. KEY DATES: su
 bmissions open 29 June 2026\, close 22 July 2026\, with notifications by 1
 5 August 2026. Apply and read the FAQ via the Eventival page linked from t
 he RE:Focus Fund site\; questions to industry@insideout.ca.\n\nOrganisatio
 n: Inside Out (Toronto 2SLGBTQ+ Film Festival)\nLocation: Toronto\, Canada
  (Inside Out is a Canadian organisation\; international projects may apply
 \, see FAQ)\nAward: Post-production grant funding to support the completio
 n and promotion of short and feature films\; the requested amount is set b
 y the applicant (see the FAQ 'How much funding can I request?'). Since 201
 8 the RE:Focus Fund has distributed more than CAD 300\,000 in grants and p
 rograms. No application fee.\nDuration: One-off post-production grant\n\nM
 ore: https://insideout.ca/initiatives/re-focus-fund/?utm_source=artificial
 nouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://insideout.ca/initiatives/re-focus-fund/?utm_source=artificialno
 uveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Toronto\, Canada (Inside Out is a Canadian organisation\; internat
 ional projects may apply\, see FAQ)
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:cada-walden-fire-station-library-public-art-2026@artificialnouveau.gith
 ub.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T115003Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260728
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260729
SUMMARY:Deadline: Call to Artists: Walden Fire Station and Library (Calgary
  Arts Development)
DESCRIPTION:Calgary Arts Development (CADA) is seeking an artist or artist 
 team to join The City of Calgary's Walden Fire Station and Library project
  team to create permanent public artwork(s) for a combined fire station an
 d library planned for the community of Walden. One artist/artist team will
  be selected with a total project budget of CAD 275\,000 (exclusive of all
  applicable taxes)\; the opportunity is open to local and national profess
 ional artists/artist teams working in various media. ELIGIBILITY: local an
 d national mid-career to late-career professional public artists and artis
 t teams with a minimum of five years' previous experience creating artwork
  in the public realm\; they must have at least three outdoor permanent pub
 lic art installations\, each with a lifespan of over 10 years and a minimu
 m project budget of CAD 150\,000 (see the Canada Council for the Arts defi
 nition of a professional artist). Walden does not currently have an active
  community association\, so the project requires experience in artist-led 
 community engagement and a strong understanding of alternative outreach. A
 rtists must be available to meet the project timelines from September 2026
  to the end of concept and design by July 2027\; fabrication and installat
 ion take place in Phase 2\, starting in the second half of 2027 and contin
 uing into 2028. REWARD: total project budget CAD 275\,000 (artist fee CAD 
 68\,750 + GST)\; CADA is open to adapting the budget breakdown to the arti
 st's approach\, following CARFAC's recommendation of a minimum 20% to the 
 artist's fee\, though the total budget will not be increased. TIMELINE: ap
 plications open 16 June 2026 (9am MT)\; pre-recorded information session p
 osted early July\; application deadline 28 July 2026 (no applications acce
 pted after 1pm MT)\; shortlisted interviews mid-September\; results late S
 eptember 2026. Eligibility questions: walden@calgaryartsdevelopment.com.\n
 \nOrganisation: Calgary Arts Development (CADA)\nLocation: Walden communit
 y\, Calgary\, Alberta\, Canada. Open to local and national (Canadian) prof
 essional artists/artist teams.\nAward: Total project budget of CAD 275\,00
 0 (exclusive of all applicable taxes) for one selected artist/artist team.
  The artist fee for the total project is CAD 68\,750 + GST. Budget breakdo
 wn can be adapted to the artist's approach\, following CARFAC's recommenda
 tion that a minimum 20% of the budget go to the artist's fee\; the total a
 llocated budget will not be increased.\nDuration: Concept and design from 
 September 2026 to end of July 2027\; fabrication and installation (Phase 2
 ) from the second half of 2027 into 2028.\n\nMore: https://calgaryartsdeve
 lopment.com/public-art/opportunities/all/call-to-artists-walden-fire-stati
 on-and-library/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://calgaryartsdevelopment.com/public-art/opportunities/all/call-to
 -artists-walden-fire-station-and-library/?utm_source=artificialnouveaugran
 tdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Walden community\, Calgary\, Alberta\, Canada. Open to local and n
 ational (Canadian) professional artists/artist teams.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:sat-lab7-performing-arts-technology-residency-montreal-2026@artificialn
 ouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T115003Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260831
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260901
SUMMARY:Deadline: SAT x LAB7: Performing Arts and Technology Research-Creat
 ion Residency 2026 (Montreal)
DESCRIPTION:The Societe des arts technologiques (SAT) and LAB7 (the researc
 h-creation lab of 7 Fingers / Les 7 Doigts) offer research-creation reside
 ncies at the intersection of performing arts and technology\, on the theme
  of human movement. Each selected project receives a CAD 10\,000 grant\, r
 oughly two weeks (about 10 days) of studio workspace at the 7 Fingers Crea
 tion Centre in Montreal\, and personalised coaching from the SAT and LAB7 
 teams. Open to non-profit organisations\, collectives and independent arti
 sts working between performing arts and technological arts\; the call is e
 ffectively open internationally\, with no nationality restriction stated. 
 No application fee. Results are announced in early October 2026. Applicati
 on deadline: 31 August 2026\, 17:00. Apply via the official open-call page
 .\n\nOrganisation: Societe des arts technologiques (SAT) in partnership wi
 th LAB7 / 7 Fingers (Les 7 Doigts)\nLocation: Montreal\, Canada. Open inte
 rnationally\; no nationality restriction stated.\nAward: CAD 10\,000 grant
  per selected project\, plus roughly two weeks (about 10 days) of studio w
 orkspace at the 7 Fingers Creation Centre and personalised coaching from t
 he SAT and LAB7 teams. No application fee.\nDuration: Around two weeks (10
  days) of in-studio residency.\n\nMore: https://sat.qc.ca/en/calls/perform
 ing-arts-and-technology-research-creation-residencies-sat-x-lab7?utm_sourc
 e=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://sat.qc.ca/en/calls/performing-arts-and-technology-research-crea
 tion-residencies-sat-x-lab7?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medi
 um=referral
LOCATION:Montreal\, Canada. Open internationally\; no nationality restricti
 on stated.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:fluxus-experimental-film-festival-call-2026@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T115003Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260715
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260716
SUMMARY:Deadline: Fluxus Experimental Film & Media Arts Festival 2026: Call
  for Submissions
DESCRIPTION:Fluxus is a contemporary short film and media arts festival hos
 ted in partnership between Factory Media Centre\, Hamilton Artists Inc and
  McMaster University School of the Arts. Its mission is to provide an acce
 ssible forum for the exhibition of creative\, experimental\, moving-image 
 art forms\, and to develop connections between Canadian media artists\, ar
 ts institutions and the public. Fluxus showcases experimental and boundary
 -pushing media works from artists of all levels working in Canada\; submis
 sions are free and unrestricted by theme\, open to a spectrum of artforms 
 including but not limited to animation\, documentary\, video art\, collage
  film\, music video and experimental film. The festival takes place over t
 wo screenings at Hamilton Artists Inc on Friday 18 and Saturday 19 Septemb
 er 2026 (the Friday screening is dedicated to emerging media artists and f
 ilmmakers)\; all screenings are free to attend. REMUNERATION: there is no 
 submission fee\, and IMAA-scale artist remuneration is paid to successful 
 applicants within 30 days of the screenings. GUIDELINES: artists must be c
 urrently based and/or working in Canada\; work must be short format (15 mi
 nutes or less) and no more than 5 years old (2021 or later)\; submissions 
 are digital Vimeo or YouTube links (private/password-protected accepted if
  the password is provided)\; solo artists\, groups\, collectives and colla
 borative works are welcome\, with a limit of one submission per artist/gro
 up/collective\; films must be independent projects over which the artist r
 etains full creative and artistic control. AI POLICY: Fluxus discourages t
 he use of generative AI in submitted works\; if AI factors into the creati
 ve process\, its use must be declared and described (see Factory Media Cen
 tre's Policy on the Use of Generative AI). APPLY via the online submission
  form with an artist bio (75 words max)\, artist CV (PDF\, 3 pages max)\, 
 a brief description of the work (100 words max)\, entry information\, the 
 video link\, and two image stills. Notification is expected in August\; du
 e to the high quantity of submissions\, only selected artists will be cont
 acted. Fluxus is committed to equity and strongly encourages applications 
 from Black and Indigenous artists\, persons with disabilities\, ethnic or 
 racial minorities\, immigrants and refugees\, Francophones\, LGBTQI+ perso
 ns\, women\, and persons of all socio-economic backgrounds. Deadline: Wedn
 esday 15 July 2026 at 11:59pm EST. Questions: programming@theinc.ca.\n\nOr
 ganisation: Hamilton Artists Inc.\, in partnership with McMaster Universit
 y School of the Arts and Factory Media Centre\nLocation: Hamilton\, Ontari
 o\, Canada\; submitting artists must be currently based and/or working in 
 Canada.\nAward: Free to submit (NO entry fee). IMAA-scale artist remunerat
 ion (a screening/exhibition fee following the Independent Media Arts Allia
 nce fee schedule) is paid to successful applicants within 30 days of the s
 creenings.\nDuration: Two screenings\, 18 and 19 September 2026\n\nMore: h
 ttps://www.theinc.ca/fluxus-call-submissions?utm_source=artificialnouveaug
 rantdesk&utm_medium=referral
URL:https://www.theinc.ca/fluxus-call-submissions?utm_source=artificialnouv
 eaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Hamilton\, Ontario\, Canada\; submitting artists must be currently
  based and/or working in Canada.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:ottawa-vanier-artist-in-residence-2027@artificialnouveau.github.io
DTSTAMP:20260713T115003Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260626
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20260627
SUMMARY:Deadline: City of Ottawa: Vanier Artist-in-Residence 2027 (RFQ)
DESCRIPTION:The City of Ottawa Public Art Program invites professional arti
 sts or artist teams to submit qualifications to be Vanier's Artist-in-Resi
 dence\, a community-led initiative designed to foster meaningful engagemen
 t and dialogue with the Vanier community\, with the insights gained inform
 ing the creation of a final legacy artwork. The community is looking for a
  reliable\, collaborative\, and adaptable artist or team\; the role will b
 enefit from candidates with diverse community engagement experience\, curr
 ent or past ties to Vanier\, and the ability to communicate fully in both 
 official languages. After the residency\, the artist or team will be asked
  to provide a proposal for a legacy artwork\, with an additional budget an
 d timeline to plan and implement it. This two-stage competition is held un
 der the Public Art Policy as a Request for Qualifications. BUDGET: CAD 40\
 ,000 plus HST for the Artist-in-Residence (March to September 2027)\, incl
 usive of all residency costs such as consultations\, research\, program ac
 tivities\, materials\, deliverables\, and the artist's time\, travel\, and
  meeting attendance\; plus CAD 40\,000 to 70\,000 for the legacy public ar
 t installation (Summer 2028)\, covering design\, fabrication\, insurance\,
  storage\, transport\, installation\, engineering\, permits\, and anchorin
 g\, as well as the artist's time and travel. ELIGIBILITY: an equal-opportu
 nity project open to local\, national\, and international professional art
 ists and artist teams with experience creating permanent public art and wo
 rking with multidisciplinary teams\; City of Ottawa employees are not elig
 ible. Applications from First Nations\, Inuit\, and Metis artists are welc
 omed and encouraged. VISION: the selected artist participates in existing 
 Vanier programming and establishes new opportunities for community interac
 tion and collaboration\, conducts historical research into the neighbourho
 od\, and proposes a permanent legacy artwork celebrating Vanier's history 
 and diversity. Application deadline: 26 June 2026\, 11:59 pm Eastern Dayli
 ght Time\, via the online form.\n\nOrganisation: City of Ottawa Public Art
  Program\nLocation: Vanier\, Ottawa\, Ontario\, Canada (in-person residenc
 y)\nAward: CAD 40\,000 plus HST if applicable for the Artist-in-Residence 
 (inclusive of all residency costs)\, with an additional CAD 40\,000 to 70\
 ,000 available afterward to create a final legacy public artwork. No appli
 cation fee.\nDuration: Residency March 2027 to September 2027\; legacy pub
 lic art installation Summer 2028\n\nMore: https://ottawa.ca/en/arts-herita
 ge-and-events/funding-calls-and-opportunities/calls-and-opportunities-cult
 ure/calls-and-opportunities-public-art-program/request-qualifications-vani
 er-artist-residence/opportunity?utm_source=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_
 medium=referral
URL:https://ottawa.ca/en/arts-heritage-and-events/funding-calls-and-opportu
 nities/calls-and-opportunities-culture/calls-and-opportunities-public-art-
 program/request-qualifications-vanier-artist-residence/opportunity?utm_sou
 rce=artificialnouveaugrantdesk&utm_medium=referral
LOCATION:Vanier\, Ottawa\, Ontario\, Canada (in-person residency)
END:VEVENT
